Neonatal Marfan syndrome, in contrast to classical Marfan syndrome, is 
characterized by rapidly progressive multi-valvular cardiac disease and death 
from congestive heart failure, typically within the first year of life. Due to 
the rarity of this condition, treatment for neonatal Marfan syndrome has not 
been well studied. In this report, a combination of losartan and propranolol 
reduced the aortic root dilatation rate after three months of losartan therapy. 
Genetic analysis in this patient revealed a mutation in exon 25 of the FBN1 
gene, which typically results in a shorter life expectancy. However, the 
patient's heart failure was controlled by losartan, propranolol and other 
anti-congestive medications, which may have prolonged his survival.

